{
  "doc_id": "20718",
  "text": "Could mTORC2 perform other functions in the translation complex that ultimately allows TM site phosphorylation? Like mTORC1, which regulates a number of translation-related events, including S6K phosphorylation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ), mTORC2 may perform other functions during translation that could promote Akt-TM phosphorylation either directly or indirectly. Some reports proposed that a Pro-directed kinase (e.g., ERK, JNK, CDK) is the likely relevant direct TM site kinase [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . So far, prolonged pharmacological treatment to inhibit activities of these kinases did not abolish TM site phosphorylation (data not shown), unlike the effects seen upon mTORC2 inhibition ( Figure 3E ; [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Whether other Pro-directed kinases may be mTORC2-dependent remains to be investigated.",
